<subSubSection type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageNumber="324">
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181805" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole midas Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole midas Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="324" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="midas">Pheidole midas</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="324">Types Mus. Comp. Zool. Harvard.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="etymology">
<paragraph pageNumber="324">Etymology Gr Midas, mythical king whose touch turned everything to gold; with reference to the color of the workers.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageNumber="324">
Diagnosis A small yellow member of the 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33735" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole fallax Mayr" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole fallax Mayr" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="324" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fallax">fallax</taxonomicName>
group characterized by the following combination of traits. Major: head heart-shaped; pilosity over all of body, and especially clypeus, mesosoma, waist, and gaster, very long, dense, and erect to suberect; a large-celled patch of rugoreticulum present to the side and behind each antennal fossa; carinulae on head and body almost entirely limited to the anterior half of the head, with most of the frontal lobes bare.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="description">
<paragraph pageNumber="324">Minor: occiput broad, lacking nuchal collar; pilosity very long and mostly erect to suberect; only carinulae present are the circular ones around the antennal fossae, and foveolation is limited to the meso- and metathorax and propodeum, with the rest of the body smooth and shiny.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="324">
Similar to 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181716" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole aenescens Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole aenescens Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="324" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aenescens">aenescens</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181717" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole alienata Borgmeier" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole alienata Borgmeier" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="324" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alienata">alienata</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33614" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole bergi Mayr" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole bergi Mayr" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="324" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bergi">bergi</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181664" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole chrysops Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole chrysops Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="324" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chrysops">chrysops</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33685" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole cordiceps Mayr" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole cordiceps Mayr" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="324" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cordiceps">cordiceps</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181808" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole nesiota Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole nesiota Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="324" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nesiota">nesiota</taxonomicName>
, as described and illustrated. Measurements (mm) Holotype major: HW 0.92, HL 0.88, SL 0.74, EL 0.14, PW 0.46. Paratype minor: HW 0.50, HL 0.62, SL 0.70, EL 0.10, PW 0.34. Color Major and minor: concolorous medium yellow.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="distribution">
<paragraph pageNumber="324">Range Known from the type locality (Trinidad) as well as series from Panama, Colombia, Brazil (Para), Peru, and Ecuador.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph pageNumber="324">Biology Stefan Cover collected the type colony from a nest in a rotting stick on the floor of montane rainforest.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
